# ============================================
# SECURITY BEST PRACTICES
# ============================================
# 
# ⚠️  CRITICAL SECURITY WARNINGS:
# 
# 1. NEVER commit .env.local or any .env.* files to version control
# 2. Use different environment files for different environments:
#    - .env.local (development - never commit)
#    - .env.production (production - set in hosting platform)
#    - .env.staging (staging - set in hosting platform)
# 
# 3. For production deployment:
#    - Set environment variables in your hosting platform (Vercel, Netlify, etc.)
#    - Do NOT upload .env files to your server
#    - Use your hosting platform's environment variable interface
# 
# 4. Validate your .gitignore:
#    - Ensure all .env* files are excluded
#    - Check: git status should not show any .env files
# 
# 5. If you accidentally commit sensitive data:
#    - Remove it from git history immediately
#    - Rotate any exposed secrets/keys
#    - Consider the data permanently compromised

# ============================================
# GISCUS SETUP (Optional Customization)
# ============================================
# 
# The template includes working Giscus configuration by default.
# Follow these steps only if you want to use your own repository:
# 
# 1. Enable GitHub Discussions on your repository:
#    - Go to your repository on GitHub
#    - Click Settings > General
#    - Scroll down to Features section
#    - Check "Discussions"
# 
# 2. Install the Giscus GitHub App:
#    - Visit https://github.com/apps/giscus
#    - Click "Install" and select your repository
# 
# 3. Configure Giscus:
#    - Go to https://giscus.app
#    - Enter your repository name (must be public)
#    - Choose your preferred settings
#    - Copy the generated configuration values
#    - Add them to your .env.local file
# 
# 4. Create discussion categories (optional):
#    - Go to your repository's Discussions tab
#    - Create categories for different types of content
#    - Use descriptive names like "Novel Discussions", "Chapter Comments"
# 
# 5. Test your setup:
#    - Restart your development server
#    - Navigate to a chapter page
#    - Verify that comments load correctly

